template: SELECT * FROM qsos ORDER BY RANDOM() LIMIT 1;

name: SQL select points, multis & score
template:
select total(points) as points, 
total(ismultiplier1+ismultiplier2+ismultiplier3) as multiplier, 
count(distinct call) as totalqsos, 
CASE WHEN total(ismultiplier1+ismultiplier2+ismultiplier3) == 0
THEN total(points) 
ELSE total(ismultiplier1+ismultiplier2+ismultiplier3) * total(points)
END as score
from qsos;

*****************
After loading Sqlite node, we need to build the QSO table in the database. 

At the command prompt User (pi) type the following (everything after the $);

$sqlite3 qsos

This will create the qsos database and drop you into the database.

Now we have to create a table within the qsos database called qsos.

At the sqlite> prompt, copy everything below from & including CREATE INDEX down to the semicolon and paste into the database.  This will create a table called qsos and a table named spots.

CREATE TABLE qsos(
  "app" TEXT,
  "contestname" TEXT,
  "contestnr" TEXT,
  "timestamp" TEXT,
  "mycall" TEXT,
  "band" TEXT,
  "rxfreq" TEXT,
  "txfreq" TEXT,
  "operator" TEXT,
  "mode" TEXT,
  "call" TEXT,
  "countryprefix" TEXT,
  "wpxprefix" TEXT,
  "stationprefix" TEXT,
  "continent" TEXT,
  "snt" TEXT,
  "sntnr" TEXT,
  "rcv" TEXT,
  "rcvnr" TEXT,
  "gridsquare" TEXT,
  "exchange1" TEXT,
  "section" TEXT,
  "comment" TEXT,
  "qth" TEXT,
  "name" TEXT,
  "power" TEXT,
  "misctext" TEXT,
  "zone" TEXT,
  "prec" TEXT,
  "ck" TEXT,
  "ismultiplier1" TEXT,
  "ismultiplier2" TEXT,
  "ismultiplier3" TEXT,
  "points" TEXT,
  "radionr" TEXT,
  "run1run2" TEXT,
  "RoverLocation" TEXT,
  "RadioInterfaced" TEXT,
  "NetworkedCompNr" TEXT,
  "IsOriginal" TEXT,
  "NetBiosName" TEXT,
  "IsRunQSO" TEXT,
  "StationName" TEXT,
  "ID" TEXT type UNIQUE,
  "IsClaimedQso" TEXT,
  "lat" TEXT,
  "lon" TEXT,
  "busted" TEXT
);

CREATE TABLE spots(
  "call" TEXT type UNIQUE,
  "lat" TEXT,
  "lon" TEXT,
  "grid" TEXT
);

CREATE INDEX call_idx on spots(call);

Type .schema at the carrot prompt to confirm your database structure.  You should see everything above.

Type .exit to exit out of the database and return to the Pi command prompt.

sqlite>.exit 

Your Node Red local qsos database is now created and ready to go.  Now configure the properties of the SQLite node to create (or confirm) the node is pointing to the qsos database.  There are four (4) N1MM database nodes you need to configure.  In the sqlite node configuration screen, add the qsos database.  Names are case sensitive. 

For your contest stations. in N1MM, within the entry window, click on Config -> Configure Ports, Mode Control, Winkey,etc... -> Broadcast Data.  Click the Radio, Contacts & Score check boxes.  This enables UDP packets to be sent to the Node Red server.  Type the following in the correct Radio, Contacts & Score text boxes where the IP of the Node Red server is aaa.bbb.ccc.ddd.  Place a space after the default IP:Port to start your IP address.

Radio to aaa.bbb.ccc.ddd:12060
Contacts to aaa.bbb.ccc.ddd:12061
Score to aaa.bbb.ccc.ddd:12062

For example, the Radio text box should look like this after your done (with the default values still there).

127.0.0.1:12060 192.168.1.30:12060

In the Station Data switch node (Flow that starts with UDP 12060), you'll need to get N1MM started on all your PC's and determine the station name (typically the hostname of the computer).  You can enable the debug node and drill down into the XML data for StationName to check each UDP packet.  You'll want to get into the node and enter the station name for each of the stations you want to pull data from.

I'm using Hamdb.org to grab the lon/lat for the map.  This database is a free lookup but currently only has US/VE data with a few other select countries.  If you want world wide spots, switch over to the QRZ.com paid XML subscription.

The time to live pins on the map is set to 3600 seconds (1 hour).  You can change this within the change node after the hamdb lookup.  Be aware a station with high QSO rates, this map will get cluttered very fast and not be very useful.

Clear Stats Only Flow - This flow clears all the line graphs, bar graphs, etc on all the dashboard pages.

Delete All QSOs and Clear Stats Flow - This flow clears all the QSO's in the database and clears all the line graphs, bar graphs, etc on all the dashboard pages.  This action is preformed right before the start of the contest.

Query All Contests in DB - This flow will show you the N1MM short name for all the contests contained in the database.  The database should only contain 1 contest, the current contest.  If a database clear is not performed before the start of a contest, the stats will be calculated for all QSOs in the database.

name: Computer Name Input
info:
Computer Name Input - These are the computer names running N1MM for each radio.  Input the computer names EXACTLY how they defined on the computer name.  Be aware of upper and lower case names.  You can find the computer name by typing 'computername' in the search bar beside the start menu.  

Get Radio Computer Names - This will dispaly the computer names in the database.  

Note : the first two computer names entered into the input fields will be displayed on the N1MM Dashboard main screen (contest overview & map).

name: Contest Call Sign
info:
Contest Call Sign - This input will be used to show Reverse Beacon Spots (RBN) on the map on where that call sign is being spotted FROM.  Callsign can be entered in lower or upper case.  

As spots come in from the spotting network, it searches for the contesting callsign being used.  If it matches, it takes the DE callsign, looks that call up in a database of known RBN callsigns or looked up the DE callsign via QRZ or Hamdb.org based on your preference in which lookup database to use.
